You are right, you can achieve saving multiple types with `GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer`. But in your example, you provide custom `ObjectMapper` to `GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer` and `GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer` doesn&#39;t configure [Jackson&#39;s default typing][1] for you (you can check default constructor logic in `GenericJackson2JsonRedisSerializer`). You have to tune it on your own and add this to your ObjectMapper

    objectMapper.enableDefaultTyping(DefaultTyping.NON_FINAL, As.PROPERTY);

This will include type information to JSON. Like this

    {
      &quot;@class&quot;: &quot;com.example.Foo&quot;,
      &quot;field&quot;: &quot;bar&quot;
    }


  [1]: https://github.com/FasterXML/jackson-docs/wiki/JacksonPolymorphicDeserialization

